Quick Guide

How to use modusa?

modusa comes with bunch of useful utility tools particulary for audio but not limited to.

Installation¶

You need python version \(\ge 3.10\)

To install run the command:

[ ]:

pip install modusa

Loading an audio signal¶

You can load audio signal from local file or directly from youtube.

[1]:

import modusa as ms
import numpy as np
import librosa

# Utility Function (Ignore)
def spectrogram(y, sr, N, H, gamma=None):
    """
    Compute spectrogram.

    Parameters
    ----------
    y: ndarray
        Signal.
    n_fft: int
        Number of fft bins (samples).
    win_length: int
        Window length (samples).
    hop_length: int
        Hop length (samples).

    Returns
    -------
    ndarray
        2D spectrogram matrix.
    ndarray
        1D frequency axis.
    ndarray
        1D time axis.
    """
    import librosa

    S = librosa.stft(y=y, n_fft=N, win_length=N, hop_length=H, center=True, window="hann")
    S = np.abs(S) # Magnitude spectrum
    if gamma is not None:
        S = np.log(1 + gamma * S)
    S_fr = sr / H # Frame rate (Hz)
    S_f = np.arange(S.shape[0]) * (sr / N)
    S_t = np.arange(S.shape[1]) / S_fr

    return S, S_f, S_t

# Local path
y1, sr1, title1 = ms.load("../audio/Ankit Anand Music - Tu Hi Bta.wav", sr=None)
y1 = y1[:int(10 * sr1)] # First 10 seconds
ms.play(y1, sr1, title=title1)

Plotting¶

1D/2D Mix¶

[40]:

# y = np.random.random(100)
M = np.random.random((100, 200))

fig = ms.fig("aasm", xlim=(0, 10)) # a => aux plot, s => signal plot, m => matrix plot
fig.add_annotation([(2.3, 6, "Segment 1"), (7, 10, "Segment 2")])
fig.add_events([2.3, 3.3, 4.04, 4.5, 4.8], label="Events")
fig.add_signal(y1, np.arange(y1.size) / sr1, ylabel="Amplitude", label="Audio Signal", ylim=(-1, 1))
fig.add_matrix(*spectrogram(y1, sr1, 1024, 160, 10), label="Spectrogram", ylabel="Frequency (Hz)", o="lower", ylim=(0, 6000))
fig.add_title("Title")
fig.add_xlabel("Time (sec)")
fig.add_legend(0.95)
# fig.save("./test.png")

Distribution Plot¶

[42]:

d1 = np.random.normal(10, 50, 1000)
d2 = np.random.normal(40, 20, 1000)

ms.dist_plot(
    (d1, ),
    (d2, ),
    title="Distribution",
    ylabel="Prob. Density",
    xlabel="x",
)

Audio Recorder¶

[20]:

result = ms.record()

[ ]:

# After recording, you can run this
# to get the recorder signal array
y, sr, title = result()

Audio Converter¶

To convert any audio file from one format to another using ffmpeg.

[ ]:

ms.convert("path/to/audio.mp3", "path/to/audio.wav", mono=False)

Download from YouTube¶

Download your content from YouTube.

[ ]:

ms.download(url="link", content_type="audio", output_dir="path/to/outputdir")
